x4freetext: A beam of 14.5 MeV protons was produced
by the Livermore variable energy cyclotron. The beam
was momentum-analysed using a 90 degrees bending magnet
with a 76.2 cm radius of curvature and focused by a
quadrupole triplet to a spot at the center of a 60.9 cm
The counter telescope consisted of a
transmission-type surface barrier delta-E detector and
a lithium-drifted silicon E detector. The delta-E
detector was 100 micro-m thick operated with a reverse
bias of 350 V. The detectors were cooled to -25 degrees
by thermoelectric coolers to minimize leakage currents.
The taget of 14N was in the form of natural N2 gas,
which is 99.6% 14N. The taget of 14C was in the form
of CO2 with a 14C enrichment of 91.4%. The target gases
were contained in a cylindrically shaped cell, 7.56 cm
diameter, with a thin window (2.5 micro-m thick nickel-
